    • Use bivariate statistical tests to find out which variables are individually associated with status at a significance level <0.05.     n.var <- 100
pvals <- as.list(rep(NA, n.var))

    • Obtain 10-fold cross validation classification vectors for each model. Obtain AUC values and make an ROC plot that shows ROC curves corresponding to predictive accuracy using the training data as well as the 10-fold cross-validations. Note that there will be four ROC curves in your plot. What model was better at predicting status?
    #10-fold cross-validation
library(dplyr)
N = nrow(a4.data)
K = 10
set.seed(1234)
s = sample(1:K, size=N, replace=T)
pred_outputs.glm <- vector(mode="numeric", length=N)
pred_outputs.rf <- vector(mode="numeric", length=N)
obs_outputs <- vector(mode="numeric", length=N)
offset <- 0
for(i in 1:K){
    train <- filter(a4.data, s != i)
    test <- filter(a4.data, s == i)
    obs_outputs[1:length(s[s==i]) + offset] <- test$status
    #GLM train/test
    glm <- glm(status~., data=train, family=binomial(logit))
    glm.pred.curr <- predict(glm, test, type="response")
    pred_outputs.glm[1:length(s[s==i]) + offset] <- glm.pred.curr

    #RF train/test
    rf <- randomForest(status~., data=train, ntree=100)
    rf.pred.curr <- predict(rf, newdata=test, type="prob") 
    pred_outputs.rf[1:length(s[s==i]) + offset] <- rf.pred.curr[,2]

    offset <- offset + length(s[s==i])
}

#ROC curves - one plot of the four tests
library(pROC)
plot.roc(a4.data$status, glm.pred, ci=TRUE)
plot.roc(obs_outputs, pred_outputs.glm, ci=TRUE, col="darkblue", add=TRUE)
plot.roc(a4.data$status, rf.pred[, 2], ci=TRUE, col="darkgreen", add=TRUE)
plot.roc(obs_outputs, pred_outputs.rf, ci=TRUE, col="red", add=TRUE) 
legend("bottomright", legend=c("GLM Training", "GLM Cross-Validation", "RF Training", "RF Cross-Validation"), col=c("black", "darkblue", "darkgreen", "red"), lwd=2)

    auc(a4.data$status, glm.pred)
    ## Area under the curve: 1
    auc(obs_outputs, pred_outputs.glm)
    ## Area under the curve: 0.9355
    auc(a4.data$status, rf.pred[, 2])
    ## Area under the curve: 1
    auc(obs_outputs, pred_outputs.rf)
    ## Area under the curve: 0.9344

Both models have high predictive accuracy, but the random forest was slightly better at prediction than the logistic regression (AUC of 0.941 vs.0.936 with cross-validation). Note the 95% CI are highly overlapping so that this difference may not make a practical difference unless there is an interest in having a particular sensitivity/specificity tradeoff given by the curves in the figure. Both the logistic regression and random forest models show evidence of overfitting since the AUC obtained with training data was higher than with cross-validation (AUC of 1 vs.0.936 and 1 vs.0.941).

-How do the AUCs for the random forest compare to the internal out-of-bag error rate estimate reported by the randomForest function? Explain how the two measures were obtained.

The OOB error estimate was ~16.6% (NOTE: actual value will be slightly different each time the rf is run since it is dependent on internal bootstrapping), which is higher error than that expected for the AUC of 0.941. This estimate differs from that of the AUC since it is based on tests during the randomForest procedure that use portions of data not being used to build trees as test data, and thus, uses trees that are based on different variables and portions of data. The AUC training and CV values are based on full random forests with many trees so their predictive ability estimate relies on different information.

The logistic regression model performs better now with only four variables, its AUC is 0.985 on training data and 0.984 on 10-fold CV, while it was previously 1 on training data and 0.936 on 10-fold CV. Thus, the logistic regression model is not as overfit as before, and its predictive accuracy has increased since noise introduced by the non-associated variables has been removed. The training AUC for the Random Forest is still 1, while its 10-fold CV one has increased to 0.968 (consistent with this improvement, the OOB error rate has improved and is now ~9.6%). Trees built during the Random Forest procedure now rely on the variables that matter most for prediction, and hence their ability to make predictions on CV and the internal test data have improved. The performance of the logistic regression is now slightly better than that of the random forest model.

  • What models would be preferable in most situations, those you created in question 4 or 5?

Those in question 5 since they are simpler, requiring 4 vs.100 variables. In addition to adding cost to a test by virtue of requiring more measurements, the additional variables add noise to the model making prediction harder. That is, they obscure significant relationships between variables and outcome. For validation studies, it would also be preferable to move forward with 4 variables rather than 100.
